<subSubSection id="75F5B03D85E6E682EC2DBB7EFC0E2E68" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="description">
<paragraph id="341F2C9A45C06024CFB9A061DD192517" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B6453C1540ED00A22944B8280D0A2B80" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">
The species differs from the other species of 
<taxonomicName id="16D30EDA506B572C0DC017FB04BBE9B8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Lepidium" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepidium" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54843A1CB16508CEC447DD9973471F47" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Lepidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence or near absence of petals, the absence of smell, larger fruits (ca. 3-3.5 mm long) in dense racemes (
<bibRefCitation id="B79FFD02BEAB8B0D79DB0B03B3C1484F" author="Tzvelev, N. N." journalOrPublisher="Saint-Petersburg Chemical-Pharmaceutical Academy, Saint-Petersburg" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" refId="B7033104" refString="Tzvelev, N. N., 2000. Manual of vascular plants of North-Western Russia (Leningrad, Pskov and Novgorod Regions). Saint-Petersburg Chemical-Pharmaceutical Academy, Saint-Petersburg" title="Manual of vascular plants of North-Western Russia (Leningrad, Pskov and Novgorod Regions)" year="2000">Tzvelev 2000</bibRefCitation>
), as well as stems and pedicels with very short capitate pubescence (D. German, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7A5DA2EBCBE050F934BA0980352B892E" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4E86C399D6D649CF7A328A41D81D8E2E" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Distribution</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C81A868519D93E5DBBC876307975718D" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="native distribution">
<paragraph id="4DDD5BF63569B578B70FD7A46B588272" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Native distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F6C406DB69B59106AA5290EDEA2CEBCE" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3188E6D0263FCC747D5E27A20379013E" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="secondary distribution">
<paragraph id="D18DB57D3543DD3EC0B16B932144305F" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Secondary distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7781CFC1DD35DA80365A2575A3D6A5D0" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Europe, Asia, South America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="836138265738DCCA02BF2ED0DA27B80C" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="distribution in neighbouring territories">
<paragraph id="08D20A22565A3B9A62EE42FD9AB162D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">Distribution in neighbouring territories</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1F0A81C20FCCA392D294F1797591DED" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">
Common and fully naturalised in southern Finland, rare casual in northern Finland (
<bibRefCitation id="18048853EAB9F9F16FCA054948AF2216" author="Suominen, J." journalOrPublisher="Luonnontieteellinen keskusmuseo, Helsinki" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" refId="B7050816" refString="Suominen, J., 1998. Retkeilykasvio. Luonnontieteellinen keskusmuseo, Helsinki" title="Retkeilykasvio" year="1998">Suominen 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Rather rare but established in southern Karelia (
<bibRefCitation id="DCC326FFB2A0D3B939BEFDD7F5BEBFFE" author="Kravchenko, A. V." journalOrPublisher="Karelian Research Centre, Petrozavodsk" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" refId="B7030339" refString="Kravchenko, A. V., 2007. A compendium of the Karelian flora (vascular plants). Karelian Research Centre, Petrozavodsk" title="A compendium of the Karelian flora (vascular plants)" year="2007">Kravchenko 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Common and fully naturalised in North-Western European Russia (
<bibRefCitation id="BA064E62E6B30FE4F728BEBEEF21C43B" author="Tzvelev, N. N." journalOrPublisher="Saint-Petersburg Chemical-Pharmaceutical Academy, Saint-Petersburg" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" refId="B7033104" refString="Tzvelev, N. N., 2000. Manual of vascular plants of North-Western Russia (Leningrad, Pskov and Novgorod Regions). Saint-Petersburg Chemical-Pharmaceutical Academy, Saint-Petersburg" title="Manual of vascular plants of North-Western Russia (Leningrad, Pskov and Novgorod Regions)" year="2000">Tzvelev 2000</bibRefCitation>
), included in the list of most invasive plants in Russia (
<bibRefCitation id="D12D978B72DF2E70D3F098DA8D250487" author="Vinogradova, Yulia" journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" pagination="1931 - 1943" refId="B7050920" refString="Vinogradova, Yulia, Pergl, Jan, Essl, Franz, Hejda, Martin, van Kleunen, Mark, CONTRIBUTORS, REGIONAL, Pysek, Petr, 2018. Invasive alien plants of Russia: insights from regional inventories. Biological Invasions 20 (8): 1931 - 1943" title="Invasive alien plants of Russia: insights from regional inventories" volume="20" year="2018">Vinogradova et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BE7FC11AAEF156F5454C67E6E21D1A0C" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166" type="new record">
<paragraph id="584A3B33D43BF35A328CE8C45B37FD41" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">New record</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C9D127440E76CCF34B387E3BB76AFC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="78166">
